#week-title("Four", "Cohobating Plant Essence over Mineral Salt")

=== Core Teaching

This week brings together the two streams of Month 7: a prepared mineral salt
(either salt of tartar or conditioned sea salt) is used as the substrate for
a cohobation with a plant essence.

*This is an experimental crossing of the vegetable-mineral border in a
controlled and deliberate manner.* It differs from the Year One cohobation in
a crucial way: in Year One, the student always cohobated a plant essence over
the same plant's salt — the three principles of one plant reuniting. Here, the
student is uniting a plant essence with a mineral salt of a different origin.

The tradition is explicit that mixing kingdoms carelessly produces no alchemical
result. However, the border zone between kingdoms is not an absolute wall — the
alchemical tradition describes several preparations that deliberately work at
this border. The salt of tartar, derived from plant ash, occupies the border
naturally: it is vegetable in origin but mineral in its character and behaviour.
Working with it as a mineral substrate for a plant essence is therefore a
border operation, not a confusion of kingdoms.

*What to observe:* Does the mineral salt absorb the plant essence? Does the
colour of the liquid change during cohobation? Does the preparation acquire any
quality — in scent, in feel, in visual character — that neither the salt nor the
essence had separately? Record observations without expectation. The purpose of
this experiment is sensory development and philosophical understanding, not
production of a usable medicine.

After two weeks of gentle digestion, examine the preparation and record its
characteristics. Compare it to a straightforward plant salt cohobation (the Year
One type) using the same source plant. Document the differences in the Materia
Medica notebook.

#lab[
  *Border Cohobation Protocol*
  + Prepare the mineral salt (salt of tartar or conditioned sea salt): lightly
    warm in a dish to remove excess moisture before use.
  + Weigh a small quantity (2–5 grams) into a glass flask.
  + Add your plant essence (Melissa tincture or hydrosol) in the same ratio used
    for Year One cohobation.
  + Seal and label with date, contents, and note: "mineral salt base — border
    experiment."
  + Place in gentle warmth. Monitor weekly; record colour changes in liquid.
  + After two weeks: assess absorption. Does the salt show any change in texture
    or colour? Does the liquid show any change in clarity or scent?
  + Document in Materia Medica notebook.
]

=== Topics This Week

- The controlled border cohobation: plant essence over mineral salt
- Comparing border cohobation results to a plant-salt cohobation
- Documenting cross-kingdom experimental observations
- Updating the Materia Medica notebook: recording the experimental preparation

#inner-work[
  *The Border as Teacher*

  Every significant transition in a life — every crossing from one kingdom to
  another — requires a period of adjustment in which neither the old identity
  nor the new has fully formed. This is the border zone.

  Journal on a border crossing in your own experience: a period when you were
  genuinely neither one thing nor another. What was required of you in that
  time? What dissolved? What crystallised?
]

